text:
I’m interested to hear others’ thoughts but, while I like the media player visually, it feels the most disconnected from the rest of the app experience. I also think that we have the potential to show a range of discoveries (which I liked about some of the other explorations - i can see that there’s a meditation dx and a nutrition dx) Post launch there will be discoveries that do not have media players so I am not sure how well this media player represents the full discovery experience.

Re: the workouts screen, if what we are trying to sell through is the idea of effortless, location-based workout tracking, my inclination would be to keep it to a single workout and include a map snippet as we have in the visual designs. This helps to convey location visually instead of making the user read the caption.
<@U0260V1BX>: Is the map still in 1.0?
yes
Okay! Yes, we agree, for some reason we thought it wasn’t going to be there for launch.
On the auto-tracking screen, can we use a workout that would happen  in one spot (not running or walking, where you cover distance?). Like Yoga or some other type of gym workout?
That is a good point. We’ll switch it to yoga.

text:
regarding the onboarding stuff. my only concern is that what we have now is almost exactly what we shared with scott two full days ago. And for me, it doesn’t show that we’ve been willing to explore more alternatives. Maybe it was just me, but I didn’t really get the feeling that we were only a few tweaks away on Wednesday. I think what we have is good, but we were tasked with finding more of a middle ground. I just don’t think we’ve gone to the middle quite far enough.

Things like the splash screen, the app icon should be considered in this onboarding experience. I also think we should show a few alternatives to the device mockup itself. Is black the only possible answer? Is grey-on-grey our only idea for color?

especially after seeing all of the branding and build-outs for the device. I think we got a nice peek into what compass/chameleon is going to be, and want to see us at least trying to follow that momentum
From the meeting with Scott I was under the impression that the Germany team will be design the splash screen…
We left it as needing to connect with him after he has a meeting with them Friday, and I’m guessing it will fall on us since he mentioned they have very little bandwidth
Plan is to follow up with him first thing next week on that front if we don’t hear back before then

<@U0260V1BX|melissa> uploaded a file: <https://uncorked.slack.com/files/melissa/F20N1R91B/screen_shot_2016-08-11_at_7.14.27_pm.png|Screen Shot 2016-08-11 at 7.14.27 PM.png> and commented: hey <!channel> - would love your thoughts on this. Audio and Video previews are out for launch, meaning that the only possible content for the bottom white area would be an extra information link, which may or may not be there. My inclination is to move the description down below the photo which will a) give the white body area more of a reason for being,  b) give the photo some more breathing room and c) align the photo treatment with other states of this same screen. If we made this shift, I would also want to shorten the photo a little bit to allow the user to see/read the beginning of the description. I know these are some last minute changes and I’m coming into this with less context than the people who have been in the weeds on these comps so wanted to hear the teams’ thoughts. Moving the description down below the photo gives us the added flexibility of being able to add goal context to this page post-launch in a way that makes sense (in the wires we had the goal context up above the description, as it sets the stage for why this discovery is relevant to the user).
